<div id="subtree-container" class="subtree-container"><div class="aea2d7dde423afa7ad9351a0886150a8-scss b51b00c1669ad99a1c607cd1e77c2824-scss" style="inset: 181px 269px 0px 0px; justify-content: flex-end;"><div class="afeebf1df237d4103108ba40799802d6-scss"><div class="c13443431e58facf06f9d12490b92a82-scss" style="width: 90vw; max-width: 8.5in;"><div class="_0df5ec6b9902d7d22ccfa3ebb4f35211-scss">Schedules from the Authoring Software</div><div class="e5e059a27f4c194020f0d961a3cb5989-scss" dir="auto"><div class="fr-view"><p>Ratios can be used to calculate the formwork based on the surface area of the sides and/or bottom of each element from the authoring schedule.&nbsp;</p>
<p>For example, for columns, it can be considered 100% of the sides' surface provided in the schedule.</p>
<p>For beams, they combine the bottom area with 50% of the sidesâ€™ area, to disregard the intersected area with slabs.&nbsp;</p>
<p>As for slabs, only the bottom surface area is considered.&nbsp;</p>
<p>While this method may not offer the highest level of precision, some companies deem it sufficient for the estimation phase of their projects.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div>